'''Gender essentialism''' is the theory that there are certain universal, innate, biologically- or psychologically-based features of [[gender]] (different from [[sex]]) that are at the root of observed differences in the behavior of men and women.<ref name="Hepburn-2008">{{cite book | last = Hepburn | first = Alexa | chapter = Feminist critics: hetrosexism and lesbian and gay psychology |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rfIFQIa9rFMC&pg=PA107 | title = An introduction to critical social psychology | page = 107 | publisher = Sage | location = London Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780761962106 }}</ref> In Western civilization, it is suggested in writings going back to [[ancient Greece]].<ref name="Bem-1993">{{cite book | last = Bem | first = Sandra |authorlink=Sandra Bem | chapter = Introduction | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=u2a59A74CPcC&pg=PA1 | title = The lenses of gender: transforming the debate on sexual inequality | pages = 1&ndash;2 | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven, Connecticut | year = 1993 | isbn = 9780300061635 }}</ref>{{rp|1}} With the advent of [[Christianity]], the earlier Greek model was expressed in theological discussions as the doctrine that there are two distinct sexes, male and female created by God, and that our nature is to be immutably one or the other.<ref name="Thatcher-2011">{{cite book | last = Thatcher | first = Adrian | chapter = Gender: language, power, and history |chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=hcNyAOxMLFsC&pg=PA19 | title = God, sex, and gender: an introduction |page=19 | publisher = Wiley-Blackwell | location = Chichester, West Sussex, United Kingdom | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781444396379 }}</ref> This view remained essentially unchanged until the middle of the 19th century, until [[Charles Darwin|Darwin]]'s publications on evolution. This changed the locus of the origin of the essential differences, in [[Sandra Bem]]'s words, "from God's grand creation [to] its scientific equivalent: evolution's grand creation," but the belief in an immutable origin had not changed.<ref name="Bem-1993" />{{rp|2}}

It was not until the middle of the 20th century and the writings of [[second-wave feminism]] starting with [[Simone de Beauvoir]] that the first alternative theory for gender difference was proposed.  This theory was developed by feminist theorists in the 1960s, 70s, and beyond, and described gender difference as being [[social construction of gender|socially constructed]], namely that the origin of gender difference is not in-born, but learned from interacting in society.  Feminists are by no means unanimous in supporting theories of the social construction of gender.  Many adhere more to gender essentialism, or to some intermediate viewpoint.  The two theories — gender essentialism and social constructionism — inform an active debate about the origins of gender differences in the fields of feminism, philosophy, and sociology which are sometimes acrimonious and break out into local and national politics.{{cn|date=December 2017}}

== Manifestations ==

=== In feminism ===

In [[feminist theory]] and [[gender studies]], '''gender essentialism''' is the attribution of a fixed essence to women.<ref name=":03">{{cite book | last = Grosz | first = Elizabeth A. | author-link = Elizabeth Grosz | title = Space, time, and perversion: essays on the politics of bodies | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 1995 | url = https://books.google.com/books/about/Space_Time_and_Perversion.html?id=Htf7y-rcVFwC | isbn = 9780415911368 }}</ref> Women's essence is assumed to be universal and is generally identified with those characteristics viewed as being specifically feminine.<ref name=":03" /> These ideas of femininity are usually related to biology and often concern psychological characteristics such as nurturance, empathy, support, non-competitiveness, etc.<ref name=":03" /> Feminist theorist [[Elizabeth Grosz]] states in her 1995 publication, ''Space, Time and Perversion: Essays on the Politics of Bodies'', that essentialism "entails the belief that those characteristics defined as women's essence are shared in common by all women at all times. It implies a limit of the variations and possibilities of change—it is not possible for a subject to act in a manner contrary to her essence. Her essence underlies all the apparent variations differentiating women from each other. Essentialism thus refers to the existence of fixed characteristic, given attributes, and ahistorical functions that limit the possibilities of change and thus of social reorganization."<ref name=":03" />

Furthermore, biologism is a particular form of essentialism that defines women's essence in terms of biological capacities.<ref name=":03" /> This form of essentialism is based on a form of reductionism, meaning that social and cultural factors are the effects of biological causes.<ref name=":03" /> Biological reductivism "claim[s] that anatomical and physiological differences—especially reproductive differences—characteristic of human males and females determine both the meaning of masculinity and femininity and the appropriately different positions of men and women in society".<ref name=":43">{{cite journal | last = Diquinzio | first = Patrice | title = Exclusion and essentialism in feminist theory: the problem of mothering | journal = [[Hypatia (journal)|Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy]] | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = 1&ndash;20 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1527-2001.1993.tb00033.x | jstor = 3810402 | date = Summer 1993 | url = https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1527-2001.1993.tb00033.x | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> Biologism uses the functions of reproduction, nurturance, neurology, neurophysiology, and endocrinology to limit women's social and psychological possibilities according to biologically established limits.<ref name=":03" /> It asserts the science of biology to constitute an unalterable definition of identity, which inevitably "amounts to a permanent form of social containment for women".<ref name=":03" /> Naturalism is also a part of the system of essentialism where a fixed nature is postulated for women through the means of theological or ontological rather than biological grounds. An example of this would be the claim that women's nature is a God-given attribute, or the ontological invariants in [[Existentialism|Sartrean existentialism]] or [[Sigmund Freud|Freudian psychoanalysis]] that distinguish the sexes in the "claim that the human subject is somehow free or that the subjects social position is a function of his or her genital morphology".<ref name=":03" /> These systems are used to homogenize women into one singular category and to strengthen a binary between men and women.<ref name=":03" />

=== In religion ===

==== LDS ====

The official view of [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (Mormons; LDS) is an essentialist belief in gender.  The 1995 LDS statement, [[The Family: A Proclamation to the World]] states the official view, and declares gender to be an "essential characteristic" of sons and daughters of God, and an "eternal identity."  Mormon people generally believe in an eternal life, and that it would be impossible for one's eternal gender to be different from one's physical, birth sex.  Church regulations permit, but don't mandate, [[ex-communication]] for those who choose [[sexual reassignment surgery]], and deny them membership in the [[priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood]].<ref name="Copeland-2015">{{cite book |last1=Copeland |first1=Mychal  |last2=Rose |first2=D’vorah |last3=Gustav-Wrathall |first3=John |chapter=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (Mormon) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=D7XQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31 | title = Struggling in good faith: LGBTQI inclusion from 13 American religious perspectives |page=31| publisher = Walking Together, Finding the Way/SkyLight Paths Publishing | location = Woodstock, Vermont | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781594736025 }}</ref>

== Criticism and alternative theories of gender ==
{{Cleanup rewrite|the section is full of jargon; there are other articles better suited for this information, this should just summarize the topic. |section |date=December 2017}}

=== Social construction of gender ===

{{Main|Social construction of gender}}
The main alternative to gender essentialism is the theory of the [[social construction of gender]].  In contrast to gender essentialism which views differences between men and women as innate, universal, and immutable, social constructionism views gender as created and influenced by society and culture, which can be different according to time and place, and that roles societally defined as appropriate behavior for a person of that specific sex then become the standard to which members of that sex are measured against. Theories of the social construction of gender grew out of theories in [[second-wave feminism]] in the latter half of the twentieth century.{{cn|date=December 2017}} 

==== Gender performativity ====

{{Main|Gender performativity}}
[[Judith Butler]]'s theory of [[gender performativity]] can be seen as a means to show "the ways in which reified and naturalized conceptions of gender might be understood as constituted and, hence, capable of being constituted differently".<ref name=":13">{{Cite journal | last = Butler | first = Judith | author-link = Judith Butler | title = Performative acts and gender constitution: an essay in phenomenology and feminist theory | journal = [[Theatre Journal]] | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 519&ndash;531 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/3207893 | jstor = 3207893 | date = December 1988 | url = https://doi.org/10.2307/3207893 | ref = harv | postscript = .}} [http://seas3.elte.hu/coursematerial/TimarAndrea/17a.Butler,performative%5B1%5D.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Butler utilizes the phenomenological theory of acts which has been espoused by [[Edmund Husserl]], [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]] and [[George Herbert Mead]], which seeks to explain the mundane way in which "social agents constitute social reality through language gesture and all manner of symbolic social sign", to create her conception of gender performativity.<ref name=":13" /> She begins by quoting [[Simone de Beauvoir|Simone de Beauvoir's]] claim: <blockquote href="Parmenides (dialogue)">''"...one is not born, but, rather, becomes a woman."''<ref>{{cite book | last = de Beauvoir | first = Simone | author-link = Simone de Beauvoir | title = The second sex | publisher = Vintage Classic | location = London | year = 2015 | origyear = 1949 | isbn = 9781784870386 }}</ref> </blockquote>This statement distinguishes sex from gender suggesting that gender is an aspect of identity that is gradually acquired.<ref name=":23">{{Cite journal | last = Butler | first = Judith | author-link = Judith Butler | title = Sex and gender in Simone de Beauvoir's ''Second Sex'' | journal = [[Yale French Studies]], special issue: Simone de Beauvoir: Witness to a Century | volume = 72 | pages = 35&ndash;49 | publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/2930225 | jstor = 2930225 | date = 1986 | url = https://doi.org/10.2307/2930225 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> This distinction between sex, as the anatomical and factic aspects of the female body, and gender, as the cultural meaning that forms the body and the various modes of bodily articulation, means that it is "no longer possible to attribute the values or social functions of women to biological necessity".<ref name=":23" /> Butler interprets this claim as an appropriation of the doctrine of constituting acts from the tradition of phenomenology.<ref name=":13" /> Through this understanding Butler concludes that "gender is in no way a stable identity or locus of agency from which various acts proceed; rather, it is an identity tenuously constituted in time—an identity instituted through the stylization of the body and, hence, must be understood as the mundane way in which bodily gestures, movements and enactments of various kinds constitute the illusion of an abiding gendered self".<ref name=":13" /> 

Candace West and Sarah Fenstermaker also conceptualize gender "as a routine, methodical, and ongoing accomplishment, which involves a complex of perceptual, interactional and micropolitical activities that cast particular pursuits as expressions of manly and womanly 'natures'" in their 1995 text ''Doing Difference''.<ref name=":53">{{cite journal | last1 = West | first1 = Candace | last2 = Fenstermaker | first2 = Sarah | title = Doing difference | journal = [[Gender & Society]] | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 8&ndash;37 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/089124395009001002 | jstor = 189596 | date =  February 1995 | url = https://doi.org/10.1177/089124395009001002 | ref = harv | postscript = .}} [http://www.csun.edu/~snk1966/Doing%20Difference.pdf Pdf.]</ref>

This does not mean that the material nature of the human body is denied, instead, it is re-comprehended as separate from the process by which "the body comes to bear cultural meanings".<ref name=":13" /> Therefore, the essence of gender is not natural because gender itself is not a natural fact.<ref name=":13" /><ref name=":23" /> Gender is the outcome of the sedimentation of specific corporeal acts that have been inscribed through repetition and rearticulation over time onto the body.<ref name=":13" /> "If the reality of gender is constituted by the performance itself, then there is no recourse to an essential and unrealized 'sex' or 'gender' which gender performances ostensibly express".<ref name=":13" />

==== Exclusion in feminist theory ====

===== Intersectionality =====

{{Main|Intersectionality}}
{{One source|section|date=October 2017}}
Analyzing gender has been a concern of feminist theory, thus there have been many modes of understanding how gender addresses meaning.<ref name=":43" /> However, developing such theories of gender can obscure the significance of other aspects of women's identities, such as race, class, and sexual orientation, which marginalizes the experiences and voices of women of colour, non-Western women, working-class women, queer women, and trans women.<ref name=":43" /> As a challenge to feminist theory, essentialism refers to the problem of theorizing gender as both an identity and a mark of difference. This refers to a problem for the concept of subjectivity presupposed by feminist theories of gender.<ref name=":43" /> There are arguments primarily by black and lesbian feminists that feminist theory has capitalized on the idea of gender essentialism by using the category of gender to appeal to "women's experience" as a whole.<ref name=":43" /> By doing this, feminist theory makes universalizing and normalizing claims for and about women, which are only true of white, Western, heterosexual, [[cisgender]], middle- or upper-class women,<ref name=":43" /> but which it implies are situations, perspectives and experiences true to all women. Patrice DiQuinzio discusses "how critics of exclusion see this as a function of feminist theory's commitment to theorizing gender exclusively and articulating women's experiences in terms of gender alone".<ref name=":43" /> Instead one must theorize feminism in a way that takes the interlocking category of experiences between race, class, gender, and sexuality into consideration; an [[Intersectionality|intersectional]] model of thinking.<ref name=":53" />

===== Mothering =====

DiQuinzio goes on to discuss how essentialism and exclusion work in relation to motherhood. Feminist theory which has used the idea of woman's essence to link gender socialization with exclusively female mothering, such as [[Nancy Chodorow|Nancy Chodorow's]] work, can be exclusionary and essentialist in the ways that it involves making universalizing and normalizing claims about mothers without taking social, historical, or cultural context into account.<ref name=":43" /> Judith Butler claims that "the effort to characterize a feminine specificity through recourse to maternity, whether biological or social, produce[s] a factionalization and even a disavowal of feminism altogether".<ref name=":33" /> Not all women are mothers; "some cannot be some are too young or too old to be, some choose not to be, and for some who are mothers, that is not necessarily the rallying point of their politicization in feminism".<ref name=":33" />

===== Transfeminism =====

{{Main|Transfeminism}}
Furthermore, the essentialism of gender in feminist theory presents a problem when understanding transfeminism. Instead of understanding trans studies as another subsection or subjectivity to be subsumed under the category of "woman", we understand the task of trans studies to be "the breaking apart of this category, particularly if that breaking requires a new articulation of the relation between sex and gender, male and female".<ref name=":63">{{cite book | last = Salamon | first = Gayle | chapter = Transfeminism and the future of gender | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vEDoLJvklZAC&pg=PA115 | editor-last = Scott| editor-first = Joan Wallach | editor-link = Joan Wallach Scott | title = Women's studies on the edge | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2008 | isbn = 9780822389101 }}</ref> Trans subjectivity challenges the binary of gender essentialism as it disrupts the "fixed taxonomies of gender" and this creates a resistance in women's studies, which as a discipline has historically depended upon the fixedness of gender.<ref name=":63" /> The expressions that exist in trans identities break down the very possibility of gender essentialism by queering the binary of gender, gender roles and expectations.<ref>{{Cite news|last = Jakubowski|first = Kaylee|url = http://everydayfeminism.com/2015/03/trans-people-gender-essentialism/|title = No, the existence of trans people doesn't validate gender essentialism|work = [[Everyday Feminism]]|date = March 9, 2015 | access-date = May 28, 2017 }}</ref> In recent years through the written work of transfeminists like [[Sandy Stone (artist)|Sandy Stone]], the theory around trans women and their inclusion into feminist spaces has opened, just like it has opened in respect to race, class, sexuality and ability historically.

==== Child development ====
Social categories such as gender are often essentialized by not only adults but also children, as young children are recorded to display essentialist beliefs about gender preferences and indications.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Meyer | first1 = Meredith | last2 = Gelman | first2 = Susan A. | title = Gender essentialism in children and parents: implications for the development of gender stereotyping and gender-typed preferences | journal = [[Sex Roles (journal)|Sex Roles]] | volume = 75 | issue = 9&ndash;10 | pages = 409&ndash;421 | publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] | doi = 10.1007/s11199-016-0646-6 | date = November 2016 | url = https://doi.org/10.1007/s11199-016-0646-6 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> Proponents of gender essentialism propose that young children from the age of 4 to 10 show the tendency to endorse the role of nature in determining gender-stereotyped properties, an "early bias to view gender categories as predictive of essential" which gradually declines as they pass elementary school years.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Taylor | first = Morgan G. | title = The development of children's beliefs about social and biological aspects of gender differences | journal = [[Child Development (journal)|Child Development]] | volume = 67 | issue = 4 | pages = 1555&ndash;1571 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-8624.1996.tb01814.x | pmid = 8890500 | date = August 1996 | url = https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-8624.1996.tb01814.x | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> Another indicator of gender essentialism in child development is how they begin to employ essentialist manifestation as a tool for reasoning and perceiving gender stereotyping from as young as 24 months.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Poulin-Dubois | first1 = Diane | last2 = Serbin | first2 = Lisa A. | last3 = Eichstedt | first3 = Julie A. | last4 = Sen | first4 = Maya G. | last5 = Beissel | first5 = Clara F. | title = Men don’t put on make-up: toddlers’ knowledge of the gender stereotyping of household activities | journal = Social Development | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 166&ndash;181 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/1467-9507.00193 | date = May 2002 | url = https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-9507.00193 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>

=== Post-structuralism ===

{{Main|Post-structuralism}}
{{One source|section|date=October 2017}}

[[Poststructuralism]] indicates "a field of critical practices that cannot be totalized and that, therefore, interrogate the formative and exclusionary power of sexual difference", says Butler.<ref name=":33">{{cite book | last = Butler | first = Judith|last2 = Wallach Scott|first2 = Joan | author-link1 = Judith Butler | author-link2 = Joan Wallach Scott | title = Feminists theorize the political | publisher = Routledge | location = New York Oxfordshire, England | year = 1992 | isbn = 9780203723999 }}</ref> Therefore, through lens of poststructuralism, the critique of gender essentialism is possible because these poststructuralist theory generates analyses, critiques, and political interventions, and opens up a political imaginary for feminism that otherwise has been constrained.<ref name=":33" /> A feminist poststructuralism does not designate a position from which one operates, but instead it offers a set of tools and terms to be "reused and rethought, exposed as strategic instruments and effects, and subjected to a critical reinscription and redeployment".<ref name=":33" />

