{{For|the genus of moth|Perusia (moth)}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Perusia |native_name = Perusia |alternate_name = Perugia |image = Perugia-arco etrusco.JPG |alt = |caption = Perugia, the Arch of Augustus |map_type = Italy Umbria |map_alt = |coordinates = {{coord|43|6|42.0906|N|12|23|26.1384|E|display=inline}} |location = Comune di Perugia, Italy |region = Umbria |type = Settlement |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Orientalizing period]] - [[Roman empire]] |cultures = [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]] [[Umbrian]] [[Roman civilization|Roman]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = yes |archaeologists = |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = yes |website = |notes = }} The ancient '''Perusia''', now [[Perugia]], first appears in history as one of the [[Etruscan league|12 confederate cities]] of [[Etruria]]. It is first mentioned in the account of the war of 310 or 309 BC between the [[Etruscans]] and the [[Roman Republic|Romans]]. It took, however, an important part in the rebellion of 295 BC and was reduced, with Vulsinii and Arretium ([[Arezzo]]), to seek for peace in the following year.<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |wstitle=Perugia |volume=21 |pages=278–279 |inline=1}}</ref>
It seems the city was in the Antonii's clientela since this period, as it was said by historians during imperial times.{{Or|date=August 2009}}
In 216 BC and 205 BC it assisted Rome in the [[Second Punic War|Hannibalic war]], but afterward it is not mentioned until 41–40 BC, when [[Lucius Antonius (brother of Mark Antony)|Lucius Antonius]] took refuge there and was reduced by [[Augustus|Octavian]] after a long siege.<ref name=EB1911/> Some of the refugees ran away toward Gauls to escape Octavian. A local history said they were the founders of Perouges en [[Dauphiné]] Province (France).
A number of lead bullets used by slingers have been found in and around the city.<ref>''[[Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum|CIL]]'' xi.1212</ref><ref name="Keppie2002">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Keppie|title=The Making of the Roman Army: From Republic to Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WouFAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA108|date=4 January 2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-74603-3|pages=108–}}</ref> The city was burnt, we are told, with the exception of the temples of [[Vulcan (mythology)|Vulcan]] and [[Hera|Juno]] &mdash; the massive Etruscan terrace-walls, naturally, can hardly have suffered at all &mdash; and the town, with the territory for a mile round, was allowed to be occupied by whoever chose. It must have been rebuilt almost at once, for several bases exist, inscribed ''Augusta sacr(um) Perusia restituta''; but, as we have seen, it did not become a colony until AD 251–253.<ref name=EB1911/><ref>{{cite book|title=Augusta Perusia: Rivista di topografia, arte e costume dell'Umbria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vw0FAAAAYAAJ|year=1908}}</ref>
