{{Grammatical categories}}
{{other uses2|Reciprocal}}
{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}

{{Transitivity and Valency}}

A '''reciprocal''' ([[list of glossing abbreviations|abbreviated]] '''{{sc|recp}}''') is a [[Linguistics|linguistic]] structure that marks a particular kind of relationship between two noun phrases. In a reciprocal construction, each of the [[Thematic relation|participants]] occupies both the role of [[agent (grammar)|agent]] and [[patient (grammar)|patient]] with respect to the other. For example, the English sentence ''"John and Mary cut each other's hair"'', contains a reciprocal structure: John cuts Mary's hair, and Mary cuts John's.

Many languages, such as [[Semitic languages]], [[Altaic languages]] or [[Bantu languages]], have special reciprocal [[morpheme]]s in verbs. English does not, and it generally uses ''"each other"'' or some other phrase to indicate reciprocity. Latin uses ''inter'' and the [[reflexive pronoun]] of the subject of the verb: ''inter se'' (between themselves) when the verb is third-person. Most [[Indo-European languages]] do not have special markers for reciprocity on verbs, and reciprocal constructions are expressed through [[reflexive verb|reflexivity]] or other mechanisms.  For example, [[Russian language|Russian]] marks reciprocity in [[intransitive verb]]s with the suffix -ся (self), which has also reflexive and [[Passive voice|passive]] interpretations.

