'''Renée Friedman''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Egyptology|Egyptologist]], primarily known for her work at [[Nekhen]] (Hierakonpolis).
{{anchor|History|Biography}} ==Life== Friedman received her BA from the [[University of California at Berkeley]], where her thesis was on the [[Naqada III|predynastic Egyptian]] cemetery at [[Naga ed Der]]. She earned her [[PhD]] in 1994 for work on predynastic ceramics.
In 1996, along with [[Barbara Adams (Egyptologist)|Barbara Adams]],<ref name=gruniad>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2002/jul/13/guardianobituaries.obituaries?INTCMP=SRCH Adams's obituary], Harry Smith, ''The Guardian'', 13 July 2002, Retrieved 11 October 2016</ref> she began working as co-director of the American [[Hierakonpolis]] Expedition,<ref>{{cite news|title=5600-year-old Egyptian tomb found|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/Science/5600yearold-Egyptian-tomb-found/2005/04/21/1114028488389.html|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=April 22, 2005}}</ref> which had been on a 4-year hiatus following the death of the former director [[Walter Fairservis]].<ref>{{citation |title=Nekhen News, ''Vol. VIII'' |date=1996 |url=http://www.hierakonpolis-online.org/nekhennews/nn-08-1996.pdf |publisher=University of South Carolina |location=Columbia }}.</ref>
==Works== * 1989 ''Fish and Fishing in Ancient Egypt''. Aris and Phillips, Warminster, England. [with D.J. Brewer] American University in Cairo. 1990. 109pp. 1 * 1992 ''The Followers of Horus: Studies Dedicated to Michael Allen Hoffman''. Oxbow Press, Oxford. [edited with Barbara Adams] 354pp. * 1998 ''Egypt''. British Museum Press. [with Vivian Davies] 224pp. Issued in USA as ''Egypt Uncovered''. * 2002 ''Egypt and Nubia. Gifts of the Desert''. 328pp. British Museum Press. Editor.
